Breast Cancer Binary Classification¶

Author: Thu Thi Nguyen

1.1. Summary¶

In this project, I built and optimised (Hyperparameter Tuning) a deep neural network to predict breast cancer. The task is to classify tumours into Malignant or Benign type when provided with the tumour's attributes in the dataset. This is a binary classification problem.

Similar dataset can be found here: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/uciml/breast-cancer-wisconsin-data

To find the best neural network, I tried various deep learning networks with different configurations of hyperparameters, features, intialization methods and compared their performances. The best neural network was found by using grid search (RandomizedSearchCV) method.

Second, I will find features with high AutoCorrelation score

  • There may have some features that highly correlate to the others. If the data is in that situation, the highly correlated features need to be combined and one/some of them can be removed.
  • By checking the autocorrelation score between variables, I can find highly correlated features.
  • In the function below, the input is my data set (without y-variable: the "diagnosis" column). The threshold is the correlation score limit that I want to check. The function with return a set of correlated features with the threshold limit I choose.
  • I will set the threshold = 0.7 since I want to find highly correlated features. As you can see, with threshold = 0.7, there is no correlated features found. Note that, if the threshold is set with a small value such as 0.3, there are many correlated features. But that is not what I want.
In [127]:
## Here, I write a function to sheck whether the data has highly correlated features or not.
def correlation(dataset, threshold):
    col_corr = set()  # Set of all the names of correlated columns
    corr_matrix = dataset.corr()
    for i in range(len(corr_matrix.columns)):
        for j in range(i):
            if abs(corr_matrix.iloc[i, j]) > threshold: # we are interested in absolute coeff value
                colname = corr_matrix.columns[i]  # getting the name of column
                col_corr.add(colname)
    return col_corr

Third, I will remove outliers

  • First, I can use box plots for quick views of how the data is distributed. I observed that there are many outliers in the dataset, but should I remove them?

  • Since this problem is about cancer detection, some outliers may be very important information to detect cancer. Therefore, remove all of them (which is a alot) is not a good idea.

  • Therefore, I came up with another method to remove just few outliers. I will use clustering to group the data into different groups. Only data points that are really far from all groups can be considered as outliers (since they are not belong to any group) and be removed.
In [129]:

  • The scatter plots above show me that some scatters have non-spherical shapes but very good density. Therefore, I will not use K-Means clustering (since K-Means does not work well with non-spherical shape clusters). Instead, I will use DBSCAN clustering.
  • In the function below, I will use DBSCAN for clustering my data. The function returns data points that do not belong to any cluster (by checking their lables = -1 or not).
  • Note that, I set "eps=40" to ensure very large distance for the DBSCAN clustering. Therefore, I will only remove the data points that are really far from all other points. This will help to avoid removal of useful data points.
In [131]:
def apply_DBscan(df_train, col_nameX, col_nameY, remove_id):
    dbscan.fit(df_train[[col_nameY, col_nameX]])
    
    ids = df_train.loc[dbscan.labels_==-1].index
    if len(ids)>0:
        remove_id.append(ids)
        
    return remove_id
In [132]:

1.2.3. Split training data into train set and valid set - Scale data for training models¶

One traditional method for split data is use K-fold cross-vaidation method. However, in this project, I want to try with various options and features for various type of networks, and training each Deep learning model really takes time. Therefore, instead of using K-fold cross-vaidation, I will use stratified sampling method using StratifiedShuffleSplit function inside sklearn.

In [139]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.model_selection import StratifiedShuffleSplit

X = df_train.drop('diagnosis', axis=1)
y = df_train['diagnosis']

split = StratifiedShuffleSplit(n_splits=1, test_size=0.15, random_state=42)

for train_index, test_index in split.split(X, y):
    X_train = X.iloc[train_index, :]
    X_valid = X.iloc[test_index, :]
    y_train = y.iloc[train_index]
    y_valid = y.iloc[test_index]

scaler = StandardScaler()
X_train_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_train)
X_valid_scaled = scaler.fit_transform(X_valid)

1.3. Build and Fine-tune a dense deep neural network¶

  • Here, I will try several methods of initialisation including He, Lecun and Glorot.
  • For each type of initialisation, I built a Keras model using Randomised Search CV to obtain the optimal hyperparameters and features for the model.
  • Additionally, I tried different multiple drop-out methods in between layers. However, it did not improve performance.
  • Picture below shows recommendations for initialization parameters for each type of activation function:

1.3.1. He normalisation¶

  • I developed function below to build a Sequential network. The function will automatically create a dense deep neural network based on the inputs for n_hidden, n_neurons, learning_rate, activation, optimizer, input_shape.
  • Since, the final output is binary (1 or 0), I need to add the last layer wiith only one output with the logistic activation (sigmoid).
  • The metrics to meassure model's performance is model's accuracy.
In [143]:
# First, let's create possible optimisers for my models
SGD = keras.optimizers.SGD(momentum=0.9)
Adagrad = keras.optimizers.Adagrad()
RMSprop = keras.optimizers.RMSprop (rho=0.9)
Adam = keras.optimizers.Adam(beta_1=0.9, beta_2=0.999)
In [142]:
def he_model(n_hidden, n_neurons, learning_rate, activation, optimizer, input_shape=X_train.shape[1:]):
    model = keras.models.Sequential()
    model.add (keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=input_shape))
    for layer in range(n_hidden):
         model.add(keras.layers.Dense(n_neurons, activation, kernel_initializer="he_normal",kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)))
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1, activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=False), optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model
  • Now, I will Create a KerasClassifier using built-function as he_model.
  • To fine-tune the best network, I tried following options for network's parameters:
- Number of neurons can vary from 1 to 200

- Number of hidden layers can vary from 2 to 9

- Activation function can be: "relu", "LeakyReLU", or "elu"

- Optimizer can be "SGD","Adagrad","RMSprop","Adam", which I created above.

- Learning eate can vary between 3e-4 and 3e-2 (which is small enough).
  • RandomizedSearchCV was used to find the best model. The EarlyStopping(patience=10) means that the training will stop if there is no improvement of model's accuracy after 10 trials.
  • As you can see, the best model I found is the one with following parameters: {'activation': 'LeakyReLU', 'learning_rate': 0.005172415563224279, 'n_hidden': 4, 'n_neurons': 153, 'optimizer': 'SGD'} 0.981825073560079
In [144]:
# Create a KerasClassifier
keras_clasifier= keras.wrappers.scikit_learn.KerasClassifier(build_fn = he_model)
param_distribs = {"n_neurons": np.arange(1, 200),
                  "n_hidden": np.arange (2,9),
                  "activation":["relu","LeakyReLU","elu"],
                  "optimizer": ["SGD","Adagrad","RMSprop","Adam"],
                  "learning_rate": reciprocal(3e-4, 3e-2)}

#### Using RandomizedSearchCV
rnd_search_cv = RandomizedSearchCV(keras_clasifier, param_distribs, n_iter=10, cv=3)
rnd_search_cv.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train, epochs=100,
                  validation_data=(X_valid_scaled, y_valid),
                  callbacks=[keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(patience=10)], verbose=0)

print(rnd_search_cv.best_params_)
print(rnd_search_cv.best_score_)

1.3.2. Lecun normalisation¶

  • Lecun normalisation works similar to the Glorot initliasation method, emplores a similar distribution to initalise weights, but with a slight change in the standard deviation where instead of dividing 1 by the average of fan-in and fan-out, the inputs and neurons for the layer, Lecun uses only the fan-in of inputs.
  • Similar to the previous section, a function named "lecun_model" is developed to create Sequential network based on inputs. The RandomizedSearchCV was used with the same EarlyStopping option.
In [145]:
def lecun_model(n_hidden, n_neurons, learning_rate,activation,optimizer, input_shape=X_train.shape[1:]):
    model = keras.models.Sequential()
    model.add (keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=input_shape))
    for layer in range(n_hidden):
         model.add(keras.layers.Dense(n_neurons, activation, kernel_initializer="lecun_normal",kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)))
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=False), optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

1.3.3. Glorot normalisation¶

  • Glorot initalisation employs a normal distribution with mean of zero and standard deviation of 1 / the average of fan-in and fan-out. Glorot initalisation works best with logistic, tanh and softmax activiation functions.
  • Similar to the previous section, a function named "glorot_model" is developed to create Sequential network based on inputs. The RandomizedSearchCV was used with the same EarlyStopping option.
In [147]:
def glorot_model(n_hidden, n_neurons, learning_rate,activation,optimizer, input_shape=X_train.shape[1:]):
    model = keras.models.Sequential()
    model.add (keras.layers.InputLayer(input_shape=input_shape))
    for layer in range(n_hidden):
         model.add(keras.layers.Dense(n_neurons, activation, kernel_initializer="GlorotUniform",kernel_regularizer=keras.regularizers.l2(0.01)))
    model.add(keras.layers.Dense(1,activation='sigmoid'))
    model.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=False), optimizer=optimizer, metrics=['accuracy'])
    return model

keras_clasifier_glorot = keras.wrappers.scikit_learn.KerasClassifier(glorot_model)

1.4. Implement advanced network: Deep and wide model¶

Deep and Wide is an example of a non-sequential neural network. The network connects parts of the input layer directly to the output layer, allowing the network to learn both deep patterns via hidden layers (deep connection) and more simplistic structure through the input layer (wide connection). The advantage of using this model is that regular sequential neural networks may be unable to learn simpler patterns in the input layer due to inputs running through deeper layers, which is not the case for the deep and wide model due to the wide-path, the short connection from inputs to concating layer, which are combined with the inputs traveling through the deep layers.

In this section, I will use parameters of 'model_he.h5' to implement a Deep and wide network.

In [180]:
Input = keras.layers.Input(shape=X_train.shape[1:])
hidden1 = keras.layers.Dense(4, activation=model_he_params['activation'], kernel_initializer="he_normal")(Input)
hidden2 = keras.layers.Dense(4, activation=model_he_params['activation'], kernel_initializer="he_normal")(hidden1)
concat = keras.layers.Concatenate()([Input,hidden2])
output = keras.layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid" )(concat)
model_WD = keras.Model(inputs=[Input], outputs=[output])

model_WD.compile(loss=tf.keras.losses.BinaryCrossentropy(from_logits=False), optimizer=keras.optimizers.SGD(learning_rate=0.0019378863072522369), metrics=['accuracy'])
checkpoint_cb = keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint("deep_n_wide.h5",save_best_only=True)
history = model_WD.fit(X_train_scaled, y_train, epochs=200,
                    validation_data=(X_valid_scaled, y_valid), verbose=0, callbacks=[checkpoint_cb])
model_WD = keras.models.load_model("deep_n_wide.h5")

1.5. Conclusion¶

In this project, I built and fine-tune two neural networks for binary classification problem to detect breast cancer.

  • The first model is a sequential neural network which was optimised by fine-tuning various options of hyperparameters. The optimised model has 4 hidden layers (plus one output layer). Each hidden layer has 153 neurons.
  • The second model is a deep and wide neural network and it was also optimised by considering various options for its hyperparameters.
  • It's interesting to see that the deep and wide neural network has only two hidden layers with only 4 neurons each. However, it still give a similar accuracy as the sequnetial neural network.
  • It tells a story that sometime we don't need to go with very complicated & deep neural networks with many hidden layers and neurons to get good predictions. Instead, a simple model such as the deep and wide model below still work well. Moreover, training and using this model are more efficiency than other complicated ones.
